ace-to-face training, we have to be more innovative in our approach to digital learning content. The best way to do this is to think about the wider digital landscape and how people use the internet in their own time.'),(924,96,'_intro_text','field_560ba1b2a1f36'),(925,96,'image_1',''),(926,96,'_image_1','field_560ba235a1f37'),(927,96,'image_2',''),(928,96,'_image_2','field_560ba25da1f38'),(929,96,'image_3',''),(930,96,'_image_3','field_560ba272a1f39'),(931,96,'image_4',''),(932,96,'_image_4','field_560ba279a1f3a'),(933,96,'main_body_of_text','By 2017 74% of all internet traffic will be video. People are more excited about watching video or animations than sifting through huge amounts of static content. Gone are the days when low bandwidth and connection problems were an issue when getting online. So why are so many digital learning programmes taking such a minimalist approach to visual and animated assets?\r\n \r\nThere are a number of reasons for this. In part, we still have to contend with onerous technical requirements including content management systems not designed for the types of websites being created and business assurance content that must be tracked for legal reasons. \r\n\r\nSo why isnt happening?\r\n\r\nAgencies and big companies are afraid to experiment when it comes to departing radically from the way content has been deployed over the last two decades. But we have to accept that what was once revolutionary is now old hat. User experience has come a long way and what was acceptable 15 years ago doesnt provide an optimum experience today.\r\n \r\nA core area of Tilts business is focused around online learning experiences and changing attitudes toward how people assimilate information online. In recent years we have been at the forefront of a marked shift away from traditional e-learning  solutions towards the creation of portals which host dynamic content in ways that emulate end-users typical internet experiences outside of the workplace.\r\n \r\nThe rationale for this is simple: if we pay attention to the way people choose to engage with content in their own time, we are more likely to get a higher uptake, and higher level of engagement, when we deploy content that aims to improve organisational effectiveness or productivity. We believe this change in direction is a positive, and permanent, one. It will, in time, come to replace the large-scale deployment of e-learning courses, particularly with regard to higher-level learning, soft skills and blended training-programmes.\r\n\r\nThe question that organisations, and their suppliers now face is how to increase the effectiveness of these portals and microsites. In many respects, the solutions deployed to date are still inferior to external sites that are available to our target audiences. The Internet is innovating exponentially and it wont be long before many of these portals begin to show signs of age. Users will be reminded of the difference between internal digital training and what they typically experience on the internet. There is a risk that they will feel coerced into learning rather than truly engaging with the content. The question that organisations, and their suppliers, now face is how to increase the effectiveness of these portals and microsites. Organisations may well ask whether there is a need to take further risk, at Tilt, we believe it is not only desirable, but absolutely essential, to innovate. '),(934,96,'_main_body_of_text','field_560ba292a1f3b'),(935,96,'image_5',''),(936,96,'_image_5','field_560ba32ea1f3c'),(937,96,'_','field_560bb9ca7ac4e'),(940,201,'_wp_attached_file','2015/09/codeit_featured_v2.jpg'),(941,201,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:5:{s:5:\"width\";i:960;s:6:\"height\";i:960;s:4:\"file\";s:30:\"2015/09/codeit_featured_v2.jpg\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:3:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:30:\"codeit_featured_v2-150x150.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:150;s:6:\"height\";i:150;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}s:6:\"medium\";a:4:{s:4:\"file