orphed, moved and toyed with by a new set of polygon co-ordinates and CSS transitions.  No tricks or tools were used used to get the illustrated results, code-wise or graphically. \r\n\r\nMassive kudos to Brian James for this stunning piece of work. \r\n\r\nTake a look yourself at <a href=\"http://www.species-in-pieces.com\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.species-in-pieces.com</a>\r\n\r\nMake sure you use Google Chrome to view. '),(3825,425,'_main_content_area','field_5629ec918a334'),(3826,414,'_wp_trash_meta_status','publish'),(3827,414,'_wp_trash_meta_time','1446135704'),(3828,426,'_edit_lock','1446483282:1'),(3829,426,'_edit_last','1'),(3830,426,'_pingme','1'),(3831,426,'_encloseme','1'),(3832,427,'header_image',''),(3833,427,'_header_image','field_5629edc6a3424'),(3834,427,'standfirst_text','In between projects our 3D specialist Ian Harrison decided to embark on a little experimental piece. There was an old iMac G3 sitting unused in the studio and he decided he would try to model it in 3ds Max. Below, Ian talks about the process and some of the lessons learnt through the modelling process. '),(3835,427,'_standfirst_text','field_5629ea6d8d729'),(3836,427,'image_1',''),(3837,427,'_image_1','field_560ba235a1f37'),(3838,427,'image_2',''),(3839,427,'_image_2','field_560ba25da1f38'),(3840,427,'image_3',''),(3841,427,'_image_3','field_560ba272a1f39'),(3842,427,'image_4',''),(3843,427,'_image_4','field_560ba279a1f3a'),(3844,427,'single_image',''),(3845,427,'_single_image','field_5629ea2db47b2'),(3846,427,'vimeo_id',''),(3847,427,'_vimeo_id','field_5629e91cf9252'),(3848,427,'youtube_id',''),(3849,427,'_youtube_id','field_5629e94ef9253'),(3850,427,'_','field_5629e968f9254'),(3851,427,'main_content_area','Before beginning the modelling process, I set up blueprints for various viewpoints of an iMac G3 that I had found on the internet.  This was important to ensure that the model could be built to the correct proportions.  The creation process began with adding a simple Box primitive to the scene, and moving vertices into place that aligned with the basic shape of the iMac (based on the blueprint).  Edge loops were used to allow more detail to be added to the model, as well as serving to keep certain edges hard when a turbosmooth modifier was applied.  Free-Form-Deform modifiers were used extensively to control the curves of the model.  The internal components were modelled fairly roughly as they would not be seen in detail.  The most challenging part to model was the skeletal-looking structure on the inside.  Large parts of this had to be built polygon-by-polygon.\r\n\r\nThe most important aspects to get right for realism was lighting and shading.  I wanted to recreate the feel of the original G3 commercials: Simple, clean, stylish, new.  A studio HDRI was essential for creating the crisp, glossy reflections on the coloured surface.  A single large plane light was used for the main illumination.  \r\n\r\nThe final images were rendered with the V-Ray rendering engine, with adjustments to brightness, contrast and colour being applied in post with Adobe Photoshop.  \r\n\r\nThe model is available to view in details & purchase on Turbosquid: <a href=\"http://www.turbosquid.com/3d-models/3d-model-imac-g3/820248 target=\"_blank\">http://www.turbosquid.com/3d-models/3d-model-imac-g3/820248</a>'),(3852,427,'_main_content_area','field_5629ec918a334'),(3853,426,'header_image','433'),(3854,426,'_header_image','field_5629edc6a3424'),(3855,426,'standfirst_text','In between projects our 3D specialist Ian Harrison decided to embark on a little experimental piece. There was an old iMac G3 sitting unused in the studio and he decided he would try to model it in 3ds Max. Below, Ian talks about the process and some of the lessons learnt through the modelling process. '),(3856,426,'_standfirst_text','field_5629ea6d8d729'),(3857,426,'image_1','429'),(3858,426,'_image_1','field_560ba235a1f37'),(3859,426,'image_2','430'),(3860,426,'_image_2','field_560ba25da1f3